---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import AceArt from "../components/AceArt.astro";

const description =
  "ACE Engine: PTL's first-generation allocation and cost engine. Reads scheduler exports and telemetry traces, scores workload behavior, applies safety guardrails, and produces structured JSON and HTML outputs with explicit assumptions.";
---

<BaseLayout title="ACE Engine | Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>ACE Engine</h1>
    <p class="thesis">Allocation and Cost Engine — read-only, deterministic, auditable.</p>

    <p>
      ACE reads exported scheduler records and telemetry traces, scores workload behavior against configurable
      utilization thresholds, applies safety controls that block unsafe downsizing recommendations, models
      operational impact across electricity, carbon, and water, and writes structured JSON and human-readable
      HTML you can version, diff, and share.
    </p>

    <p>
      No agent access to production schedulers. No enforcement. No changes to running systems. Every recommendation
      is traceable to a source job record. Every assumption is explicit and replaceable.
    </p>

    <div class="visual-center" aria-hidden="true">
      <AceArt />
    </div>
    <p class="figure-caption muted">Signal to structure: noisy scheduler traces become scored, reviewable outputs.</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Pipeline</h2>

    <p>
      ACE runs a deterministic, five-stage pipeline. Each stage is independently testable and produces
      intermediate outputs you can inspect before proceeding.
    </p>

    <h3>1 — Ingest</h3>
    <p>
      Reads <code>sacct</code> exports, CSV traces, or JSONL records. Applies a trace adapter layer that
      normalizes scheduler-specific field names, handles missing telemetry gracefully, and flags CPU-proxy
      records where GPU telemetry is unavailable. Validated against the MIT Supercloud HPCA22 dataset.
    </p>

    <h3>2 — Canonical schema</h3>
    <p>
      Converts raw records into ACE's canonical job schema with explicit provenance fields: source file,
      adapter version, normalization decisions, and confidence scores where measurements are inferred rather
      than directly observed. JobID normalization handles scheduler-specific ID formats across Slurm and
      other HPC schedulers.
    </p>

    <h3>3 — MSA core (score)</h3>
    <p>
      Scores each job across three dimensions: utilization summary, over-request heuristic, and review score.
      All weights are configurable. Segmentation by short jobs, utilization percentiles, duration percentiles,
      and savings buckets surfaces the distribution structure that broad averages hide.
    </p>

    <h3>4 — Safety overlay</h3>
    <p>
      Before generating recommendations, ACE applies configurable safety controls. Jobs below minimum runtime
      thresholds, jobs with incomplete telemetry, and jobs flagged by the near-zero utilization queue are
      blocked from automatic downsizing recommendations. Safety mode is explicit and logged — you can see
      exactly which jobs were filtered and why.
    </p>

    <h3>5 — Report</h3>
    <p>
      Writes structured JSON for downstream processing and a human-readable HTML report with summary cards,
      tables, and histograms. The HTML report is generated from the JSON output, so the two are always
      consistent. Both are versioned and diffable.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Running ACE</h2>
    <pre class="report-excerpt"><code>$ ace analyze --input jobs.csv --mode msa --safety-mode basic --json-out out.json
jobs_analyzed: 12840
allocation_changes: 918
risk_flag_jobs: 4861
review_queue_near_zero: 2132
review_queue_over_requested: 671
capacity_savings_usd: 18374.42
report_written: out.json</code></pre>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Scoring math</h2>
    <p>
      These are heuristics under active research, not ground truth. They are documented here so you can
      inspect them, challenge them, and replace them with your own weights.
    </p>

    <h3>Utilization summary (per job)</h3>
    <pre class="formula-block"><code>util_avg = mean(utilization_samples)
util_p95 = percentile(utilization_samples, 95)</code></pre>

    <h3>Over-request heuristic</h3>
    <pre class="formula-block"><code>over_request_ratio = requested / max(observed, epsilon)</code></pre>

    <p>
      <code>epsilon</code> prevents division by zero when observed utilization is zero. Jobs with
      <code>over_request_ratio</code> above threshold enter the over-requested review queue.
    </p>

    <h3>Review score (weighted)</h3>
    <pre class="formula-block"><code>score = w1*(1 - util_avg) + w2*log1p(requested) + w3*variance(runtime)</code></pre>

    <p>
      All three weights are configurable at runtime. Higher scores surface jobs with low utilization,
      large resource requests, and high runtime variance — the intersection most likely to contain
      actionable over-allocation.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Current status</h2>

    <p>
      ACE is in a pilot-ready read-only analytics phase. It can ingest exported scheduler data including
      Slurm <code>sacct</code> output, analyze deterministically with optional safety mode, and generate
      JSON and HTML outputs suitable for sharing with operators and institutional stakeholders.
    </p>

    <p>
      Phase 2B1 focuses on real cluster readiness: joining scheduler exports to telemetry (GPU and CPU
      utilization), robust JobID normalization across scheduler variants, and confidence and provenance
      scoring so every recommendation is traceable to a measurement rather than an assumption.
    </p>

    <p>
      No enforcement. No changes to production schedulers. That boundary is intentional and will not
      change without explicit, staged validation.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links">
      <a href="/contact">Discuss a pilot &rarr;</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
